Rating: 4
I made this for a large family style dinner (which included kids, teens and adults), so I doubled the recipe. It was devoured! Here's what I did differently; Broth - I used red wine vinegar instead of apple cider vinegar. I actually made the broth several hours ahead of time and simply let it sit. I reheated it just before I needed it. Salmon - Do have the skin removed! I pan seared it for about 2 minutes per side only (I think the time suggested was too long...I didn't want to dry out the fish). I did this about 2 hours before I intended to serve it. I put the seared fish in the baking pan, added the steamed potatoes and covered it with foil and let it sit on the counter. I followed the baking time exactly as well as the cooking time of the spinach. The broth added fabulous flavor to the potatoes. I served this in bowls...don't over ladel the broth...it's not supposed to be a soup dish!

Rating: 1
This was an ok recipe, but I think you could use the same ingredients to make a much better meal. For instance, I'd roast the potatoes in olive oil with a handful of chopped herbs, while either grilling or broiling the salmon. Then, I'd make a sauce with the shallots, butter, wine, tarragon, mustard, and maybe a bit of vinegar and broth to serve over the fish. Forget about cooking it all together in a broth in the oven. Add the sauteed spinach, and you'd have a great meal with alot more flavor than this recipe provides. As the recipe is, I'd say it is not worth a second go.

